{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631377"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:26:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:26:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17369"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17369"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.12,0.8,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10059"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70369"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10059"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17369"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55833"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5363"},{"type":"tags","id":"5379"},{"type":"tags","id":"5388"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23627"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70369"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman attends her general practitioner to discuss breast cancer screening. She has no symptoms or family history of breast cancer. The doctor explains that mammography is used as a screening test in the national breast cancer screening program.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes an essential characteristic of an effective screening test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ability to detect end-stage disease","High specificity to confirm diagnosis","Low cost with no false positives","High sensitivity to detect most cases of disease","Complex testing methodology for accuracy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most important characteristic of a screening test is \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh sensitivity to detect most cases of disease\u003C/strong\u003E. This minimises false negatives, ensuring that people with the condition are not missed. Screening tests are designed to cast a wide net in asymptomatic populations, with positive results typically requiring follow-up diagnostic testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbility to detect end-stage disease\u003C/strong\u003E - Screening tests aim to detect disease in early stages when treatment is most effective and before symptoms develop.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh specificity to confirm diagnosis\u003C/strong\u003E - While specificity has value, diagnostic tests rather than screening tests are used for definitive confirmation of disease.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow cost with no false positives\u003C/strong\u003E - Although cost-effectiveness is important for population screening programs, all screening tests have some degree of false positive results.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplex testing methodology for accuracy\u003C/strong\u003E - Screening tests should be simple to perform and interpret to enable widespread implementation in the population.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important characteristics of screening tests include acceptability to the population, safety, and cost-effectiveness. The positive predictive value of screening tests is influenced by disease prevalence in the tested population.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Screening tests should have high sensitivity to minimise false negatives when detecting serious conditions in asymptomatic populations.","The positive predictive value of a screening test increases with higher disease prevalence in the population being tested.","An ideal screening test should be simple, safe, acceptable to the population, and cost-effective."],"references":["Screening programmes: a short guide. World Health Organisation; 2020. https://iris.who.int/bitstream/handle/10665/330829/9789289054782-eng.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55833"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17369"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55833"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T19:58:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T19:59:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10059"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70369"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"